{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_jessicajones_ver01/data/sn87062237/00383342880/1920100901/0720.xml":{"full_text":"Presidential Campaigns\nXIX. The McKlnley-Bryan Race of 109ft.\nBy Frederic J. Ilaakla.\nWashington, D. C.,Dct 9.\u2014The hardest\nfought political battle of American his\ntory was the campaign of 1896 in which\nWilliam McKinley of Ohio vanquished\nWilliam Jennings Bryan of Nebraska.\nThe faiit that McKinley was re-elected\nwith case in hisseeond campaign against\nBrvan, and that the Republican majorities\nof 1896 look so great on paper, has caused\nmany men of short memory to believe\nthat McKinley won his first election with\nout great difficulty.\nIn that .year the Democratic nominee,\nMr. Bryan, made the most remarkable\nspeaking campaign ever undertaken by\nan v man. In the same year, the Republican\ncampaign manager, Mr. Hanna, spent\nfive 1 1 mes as much money as had ever been\nspent before in a presidential race. The\nRepublican campaign was conducted\nwith such consummate skill that the name\n\u00abif Mark Hanna will livo for years as that\n\u00abif the W political general the country\nha.\u00ab produced.\nHie Year 1896 was a year of political\nrevolution. Both of the leading parties\nunderwent great changes, ami the number\nof independent voters was increase\u00ab! a\nthousand fold. Mr. Cleveland's second\nadministration began with the country\nthe verge of a financial crash. The\nblow descended and thepanicof 1893 was\nThe money question, which both\nparties ha\u00abl so carefully side-stepped for\nso many years was presented in such a\nwav that the administration oould not\navoid taking a position. Mr. Cleveland\nand his cabinet decided to place the\ncountry squarely on the gold standard,\nand to disregard the jietty sops which\nhad been thrown to silver. The treasury\nregulations accomplished this purpose\nlung before the SlcKinley administra\non\non\nlion came in.\nD FAI OCRAT\u00bb IN OONTTiOt,\nFor th<* first tun\u00ab' since the first, part of\nBuchanan administration the Govern\nment was in the control of the Democrat,\nthat party having the President anil a\nmajontv in both Houses of Congress. Mr\nlevelond called (Yirgreos together ami\nIinn-d the repeal of the silver purchasing\ncl, tUse of th*' Sherman Act, which would\nflii.tliv \"demonetise\" silver. Hih party did\nnot agree with him on that subject, atul it\nwith the gn*atcet difficulty that hw\npurp. was necomplislM'il.\nPresident 'leveland hod been on rx\nof civil service reform and was\nw a>\nemp'Hr\nopposed to \"pernicious activity in poli\nto. but he went to the extreme of the\nuse of pMtronag*' a.\u00ab a club to drive the\nrepeal bill through Congress. Even then,\nit was done only by the help of eastern\nK.-publican votw. It left his partv hope\nli'sslv divided\nThe Democratic lar.lsbde which re\nct\u00abl Cleveland was th.- result of popu\n,.r disapproval of the McKinlev Tariff\n11,U of 1890. After the temfir fight on\nthe silver purchasing clause repeal, the\nI Vmocratic Congress endeavored to enact\nVn\u00abv*r\u00bbiir tanff bill The oartv wasal\n\u00bbcmocratir tann ruu. nepony wasai\nrea.lv tom asunder and could act with no\nm \u25a0inirnitv The re\u00abult w* the mssfun\nn h \\V,wh ich M r aSSS\nnf th\u00ab Wilson Hill, which Mr. tteveiami\nI*-mulled to bicorne a law vnthotlt h\u00bb\nI\n\\s ti\u00ef'pronle hmi condemned the Me\nvs t ne people nw eonnemnen uic me\n\nfcnd before cffiH-t could oossihlv have\nAid rx^ore its neci coma pcx>. imy nave\nN-en felt, bv the election of the Democratic\nDo\u00bb, m 1890 so the Wils\u00abin Bill i hanr\u00abi\n\u00ab.\u00bbuse in I8.au so me wiison run cnargni\nwith responsibility for a panic which was\nbefore th\u00ab- hill was written resulted in\n-\u00bbJ \u00abs\u00ab\nj .v \u00bbw __ U\nir\u00ab silver anil that the Democrats would\nfoliow thetr Prewdent m advocacy for\nVHZ* Wwas\nP\nA TEAR nr STITT TART IKS.\nAll through th\u00ab* three years of the Clcv\u00ab*\n1 \u00abnd Administration leading up to the\nampoign of 1896 there was constant\nMnfc m both parti\u00ab\u00bb. For a time it seemed\nthat tin- Republicans would declare for\nboth partira would declare for the gold\nM-amiard and the silver hosts would enroll\nunder the banner of Popilism. The Re\npublican\u00bb felt certain that they oould\nw .n on the prosperity issue, find by de\nnouncing the Cleveland administration\nfor it\u00bb issue of 3262,000.000 of bond\u00bb in\n\"time of profound peace.\" But tey didn t\nw ant to -pht their own forces by taking\nn.lra in the money fight.\nMr. McKinley and Speaker Thomas B\nRord were the leading candidates for the\nRepublican nomination for President.\nMr McKinley had the good fortune to\nhave Mark Hanna for his political \u00abap\nte n. Hftana orermired the states and took\neven New England away from Reed long\nbefore the convention met. Mr. Hanna\nw afraid of the money quest ion and Mr.\nMcKinley was committed by his record\nto \"bimetallism. So the Ohio leaders\nat tempt\u00ab! to 'straddle the issue once\nmore. The Ohio state platform \u00absontained\na ddphie utterance on the money ques\ntion which said nothing\nBut when the national convention met\nm Si Ijouis, Mr. Hanna found that the\nquestion was one which was too big to be\nstraddled. Senator Thomas C. Platt of\nN cw It qrk forced Hanna to accept a gold\nstandard platform. It was later modified\nbv a pronouncement in favor t\u00bbf inter\nnatt'inid liimetalliam. which jiemutted\nRepublicans who had been shouting for\nsilver to come down gracefully. Senator\nPlatt may not be regarded as a great\n-talesman, but in 1896 and 1900 be did\nr mgs that left marks on the history of\nthe oountrv.\nwestf:rver\u00ab boltkp\n'Ah en the gold plank was adopted,\nthirty-four western Republican delegates,\nheaded bv Senator Tfiler of Colorado,\n^enr.tor r a n non of Utah and Senator\nDubois of Idaho, walk\u00ab-d out of the con\nvention and into the Democratic party,\nill over the country there w\u00ab*re Repub\nlican- who loudly proclaimed the fact that\nthe- had boite\u00ab! the nomination of Mc\nKmlr A national silver Republi\u00ab\u00eean con\nvention was called. Mr. Hanna, chosen\nchairman of the rational committee, knew\nthat tie had a grtat job ahead of him and\nhe set to work.\nThe Democratic Convention met in\nChicago Th Cleveland wing of the party\ncontrolled the national committee, but\nthe recommendations of that body were\n\u00bbwept aside on the first vote and it was\nclear that the silver men \u00abjontrolled the\nconvention. A resolution commending\nthe then nresent Democratic Convention\nwas voted down with vengeful hoots. No\nman was ever bated more than the Demo\ncratic National Convention of 1896 hated\n.rover Cleveland, the Democratic Prest\nleut of the United State\u00bb,\nLeading free silver advocates like Rich\nBland of Missouri and John R.\n\u00ab\u2022Lean of Ohio were contesting for the\ntninatmn. The story of their defeat is\nmost familiar bit. of political history,\nlliam Jennings Bryan, who had re\n\u2022tod the .St. Louis convention which\nmnated McKinley, for a Nebraska\nt \u00bbpaper, came to Chicago at the head of a\ninteMtiug delegation. He wa\u00ab given a\n-C- 'Then \u00abaime the great debate \u00ab>n the\nplatform, the eastern Democrats fighting\nhard agaiost the majority. Jn that de\nMr. Brvan. then oniv thirty-six years\nold, slini of figure and full of name, learied\ninto world-wide fane m iineneii The\nfamous \"crown of thorns un\u00abi cross of\ngold \u00abpe\u00abH'h, w-liether the figure was\n,rrow\u00ab'd from Representative McCall of\nMaKnaoburetts er not, sent that conven\ntion wild. Bryan was nominated.\n-H P\n(\u25a0ate.\nLx\nTKM'MPH or THE BOV ORATOR.\nA little later the iPopuiiaU and the\nSilver Republicans also no mi uatod \"the\nBoy Orator of the Platte The Cleveland\nDemocrats called a convention at Indian\napolis and organised the \"National Demo\nnic v.\" General John M. Palmer of Illinois\nspldier of the Union, vrae nominated for\nPresident, with General Simon Bolivar\nBuckner of Kentucky, a soldier of the\nConfederacy, for Vice President. They\npolled but. few votes, the majority of the\ngold Democrats voting straight for Mc\nKinley.\nBryan soon began his unprecedented and\nunequalled campaign tour. He did not,\nthen possess the suavity of his later years\nbut he was mightily in earnest. No other\nman has qyer arouse\u00ab! the enthusiasm\nwhich he.created in that campaign. He\nspoke to over five million people, making\noVor a thousand separate sneechee. In\nthe first part of the campaign no travelled\nin ordinary day coaches, the railroads\nmaking it as hard for him as possible.\nToward the end of the campaign the,rail\nroads relented and he was enabled to get\na private ear. He was without money and\nin his great canvaes was^ornetimee forced\nto borrow tiie price of a ticket to the next\nstopping plan\u00ab-.\nAgainst this terrific campaign, which\nseemed to bo sweeping the country tor\nthe Democrats, Mr. Hanna planned, the\nKTpnt \"campaign of education. 1 he\nfarmers of the agricultural states east of\nthe Mississippi were induced to_believe\nthat the election of Bryan would menu\nbankruptcy for them. All of tlie wealth\nof the country woe back of Hanna he\nhad millions to spend and he knew how\nto do it.\nCareful canvasses token two months\nbefore the elections showed that such\nstates as Ohio und Indiana were for Bryan,\nThe work that was done to turn that de\nfeat. into the overwhelming victory of\nNovcndier was due to the political sagacity\nof Marcus A. Hanna.\nBryan's appeals to the people of every\nsection, tiie enormous popular interest in\nhis personality and the pictoreequonesa\nof lus campaign, on the one side, aud the\nefforts of the Republicans to reach every\nvoter with campaign literature said per\nsonal argument on the other si\u00ab!\u00ab, reeultod\nin a widespread popular interest in politics\nsuch as had never been known.\nWhile the campaign was decisive, and\nwhile it practically settled the money\nqiu-stion for all time, defeat did not dimin\nish the popularity of the Democratic\nstandard-bearer, who has over since stood\nhigh in the councils of his party Mc\nKinley was chosen lYesident and his\nadministration witness\u00ab! the return of\nprosperity, the greatest the country has\never known. After all.not the least among\ntiie Republican assets of 1896 was the\nfact that the panic of 1893 came during a\nDemocratic administration.\na\ni\n^9* narional cornent ms\nm the summer of 1900 everybody\nknew .hat the Republicans wtaild rnnomi\nnate President McKinlev and that the\nDemocrats would again follow the lea\u00abl\n\u00ab^P Mr H ryw\u00bb* -McKinleys re\nnomination w&s made certain because of\nthf> Kreat t prosperity which bl\u00ab^s\u00abl th.i\nof \u201erSk*\n\u00b0t with .spam, and because of the\n(f orvanisarion of the Ite\nPenection oi uic organiiouon\npubheon party under Mr. Hanna and the\nwtene of Republican senators that stoo\u00abl\n\u00abdin, e ist rat ion Brvan re\nWIT n ,n< OO ram wtrat ion. \"Gran, re\nnommation was made\u00abx-rtam by his popu\n^y with the rank and file of his parly,\nnotwithslandin* tlx- bitter and intense\nnotwixnsxanouig tn\u00ab i.nier aim mieose\nXX. THK M KliVUtt-BRTAX RACK OF 1900*\nopposition of the gold Demor-rate\nr .-nomination of Brvan in 1900\n1 ne renomma ttonot nan in i.m\nthe only instance of the raoomination of on\nful j; ri t\u00c4 a jr rwdent in the\nutsut. esMuicimainaie tor i ream, m mine\ncampaign Text after hw defeat. Jackson\nl824 b *5'T\nn s_\nthe only irstanre of the renomination of an\nunsuccessful candidate for Ihusidont in the\ncampaign rext aft\u00ab*r hrs defeat. Jackson\nwas a candidate in 1828 after hu\u00ab defeat in\n1824. but as he had the plurality of both\npopular and electoral votes in the first\nrace, and as \u00fc:ere were no party nomina\ntions then, his case is not a precedent.\nHenry Clay was three times a candidate\nfor President, but only once was he the\nrecognuz\u00ab*! nominee of a party, and that\nI was in the campaign after the one in which\ndei fo the WhlR nomination\nfcv (>noral H amson. Grover Cleveland\nnominal\u00ab! in 1892 after his deieat\n1BSS. but as lie liad nerved one term in\nWhite House be could not be oon\nthe White House be could not be oon\nsidered a wholly unsuccessful candidate.\nNo man who ha* met defeat at every\nturn of his career in national politics lias\nbeen able long to retain the leadership\nof one of the two great parties with tb\u00ab'\nsingle; exception of Mr. Bryan.\nKEW factors D. politics\nBetween the presidential campaign of\n1896 and 1900 things had happened w hich\nwere to change the whole course of Ameri\ncan national life.\nWar was declared on Spain, and in leas\nthan four months it was over The .Amen\ncan victory was complete and the United\nStates had suddenly become a \"world\npower, in the sense that the phrase is\nused in'European chancellories\nAs the result of the war the United\nStates found itself in the possession of\nseveral things it had never had liefore.\nThere were the colonies\u2014the Philippines,\nThere was the\nui\nPorto Rioo and Guam.\nprotectorate\u2014Cuba-There wa\u00bb the church\nlands question. There was the extra\nterritorial proplem and the question,\n''Does the Constitution follow tiie Hag?\"\nIn addition to these new things, the na\nUon also had a new crop of war heroes,\nChief among tliese was Theodore Hooee\nveit. Others were Admirals Dewev,\nSchley, Sampson and Lieutenant Hobson.\nMr. Hrvan had endeavored to become a\nwar hero too, but the regiment which he\neomnaanded was not permitted to get\nfurther away than Tampa.\nHOW DtWJBY gUESREl) HUISELF.\nAdmiral Dewey was the great naval hero.\nNaturally, he was discussed as a candidate\nfor President. He made the fatal mistake\nof taking the first \"mention\" as seriously\nas if it had been a call from the notifica\ntion committee of a national convention.\nHe accepted a nonunation in advance\nof its being offered, and was promptly\nlaughed into oblivion. Sampson and\nSchley were involved in a controversy\nthat removed both of them from the hero\nclass. General Joe Wheeler had been a\n\"rebel genera! and was out of the question\npolitically. General Nelson A. Miles aud\nColonel William J. Bryan \u00abiid not get\nto the front.\nThus it happened that when two year\u00bb\nhad gone by and the country faced\nanother quadrennial struggle for the Presi\ndency, it found that the \\V\nhad produced but one genuine\nw r Lo had lasted That was Colonel Roose\nvelt. He hadn't lx*m high in command\nin the Army, but he had organized\npicturesque regiment and had done many\npicturesque things. He had actually\nparticipated ir. a battle and had proved hi\u00bb\neagerness to fight.\nThe Republicans of New York State\nhad taken him up and had elected him\ngovernor, not s\u00abj much because they\nwanted turn, but because he was the omy\nman who \u00ab'omd win.\nsince, the Republican\ngovernor so selected might be entirely too\nseu-willed to rule the roast at Alb\nto suit tiie organization. In those days\nthe will ot Thom\u00e2s C. Plait wav law in th\u00ab\nRepublican organization in New Yotk\nState.\noposed it then,\ncould not hold Roosevelt down, so he\ndecided to get rid of him He would ku-k\nhim upstairs.\n'ar with Hyain\nE\nefo\nV, ir\na\nAs has. happened\nhoAses found that a\nNot even Mr Roosevelt openly\nBut Platt knew that he\nPUTTIN'\u00ab! ROOSKVKI-T IN THK WASTK BA^KI T\nTherefore lie went to the Republican\nConvention a' Philadelphia vriih ids plans\nall laid. The nomination 01 McKinley\nassure\u00ab!, although there was a little Roose\nvelt talk from the weitem State\u00bb, Stale\u00bb\n\nthat had gone tor Bryan (our jmn Mar\u00ab.\nHanna and hi\u00ab nenalarial eoterm rated\neverything. There were Platt and Qnay,\nFait banka and Allison, Depew and For\naker. Wolrott and Bodge, and the\nvent ion wa* going an they directed.\nHanna wanted Cornelius N. Bliss,\nHenator Amson nominated for Viee\nPreeident. Vice Prenaient Hobart, having\ndied in office. Piatt took Quay into\nscheme. Tney must get rid ot Roosevelt.\nSo they organised the willing westerners\nand began whooping it up lor Roosevelt\nfor \u00ab\u00bb.und place. The dangerous man was\nto be buried alive in the Vice-Presidency.\nColonel Rooseved wa.- already a candi\ndate foi President for the campaign\n1904. Ho believed that his interests could\nbe advanced more readily if he remained\ngovernor of New Y ork than if he were made\nVice lYesjdont, He protest\u00ab! with earn\nestness and vehemence. Ho fought\nhard as he possibly oould, but the enthu\nsiasm for the one war hero who had\nweathered t he storms of two years was\ngreat that it could not lie overcome.\nMore especially when managed by two\nveteran manipulators like Platt and\nQuay. So it was that Theodore Roose\nvelt was lacked upst airs and put on the\nshelf \"where he would never bother\nnational politics again.\"\nThe Democrats met in Kansas City on\nJuly 4 and the Silver Republicans met\nthe same eity on the same day.\nThere was a great fight, loti by David\nTV Hill of New York, to prevent the\nspecific reiteration of the free silver piank\nof 1896. but Mr. Bryan insisted and the\nniank went in. Admi Stevenson, who had\nbeen elected Vice President with Grover\nCleveland in 1892, was given the second\nplace on the ticket. The Silver Republi\ncans promptly nominated thesame candi\ndates. Later in the campaign the anti\nImperialisl Convention met and endorsed\nBryan. Th\u00ab Gold Democrats call\u00ab!\nconvention, but it was decided not\nmake any nominations. Many of the\nleaders of the Palmer and Buckner follow\ning came back into the jiarty and sup\njiorted Mr. Bryan, but the large majority\nof the rank and file of the Cleveland fac\ntion went into the Republican party.\nBRYAN S DIWTUIN\u00bb.\ncon\nMr. Bryan again took the stump and\nmade a great shaking tour. He was met\neverywhere with great enthusiasm, but\nhe did not stir the depths that he had\nbut Colur.ol Uoom-v.-ll look lb.- Mump\nand flayed Bryan with characteristir *eal\nMr Bryan ha\u00abi attempt\u00ab! te make\n\"impenahsm the paramount ussue in the\ncam(\u00bbugn. Many conservatives were in\ntense in their opjxisition to the inaugura\ntu>n of a \u00abJonial system. Republicans\nand conservative Democrats *h\u00ab. looked\nupon the Bryan of 1898 with horror were\nwilling to follow him in 1900. There is no\nmicstion but that the Bryan vote among\ntoo c\u00ablueat\u00abl cLioses was greater in the\nsecond campaign than th*' first\nBut among other classes Mr. Bryan\ncoukl not hohl his own The Republican*\nmade the \"full \u00ablinner j*ad\" the paramount\nissue. As for the colonial jxihey, that was\nmanifest destiny ami \u00abluty to humanity.\nThe thing to talk about was prosperity.\nIh* count rv was onvax-rmBi and was be\n1 ne country wae pnvqienHB\u00ab ano was ne\ncoming more so cvrrv day. It was enter\nnronitioiis era of its\n>ng upon tn< mom, prapiuou. ra ii\nuidustnal history. The people seldom tun,\nrail an aflministration in good times.\nTherefore Mr McKinlev was n-el\u00abvted\ninerti\u00abir\u00bb .nr. .uciunicj was n'-oiecuHi\nby much greater majority than he ha\u00abl\nct'\u00ab'iv\u00abl four years U-fore. 3 here was\nfl dirrin\u00ab the camnaien when\nnever a Umt tiunng tne campaign wnen\nMcKinlev was in anv danger of \u00ablefeat\n\u00ab\u00abwnted his nvdeetion *s\nUemoeraui accepted ru\u00bb re-wecuon as\nmatter of cours.' Ehe mingling of\nj southern soldiers in the\nnorthern and soutnern sounera m tn\nSTk\u00c4lfl\u00c4\nM d .tofULct\nMcKinley made his southern tourbe burie\u00ab!\nthe \"bloody shirt\" for all lime to come\n\nformer member of Congress, will.be the\nchief speaker at\ni Theatre. F\u00ab>urtl\nthe\nITALIAN REPUBLICANS.\nTo Hold a Meeting in the Victory Theatre\nTomorrow Evening.\nF. N. LaGuardia of New York and a\na meeting in the Victory\ni Th